WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.795
October 1971. 

00:00:02.795 --> 00:00:04.420
An American spy submarine

00:00:04.420 --> 00:00:06.600
has&nbsp;just crossed into Soviet waters

00:00:06.600 --> 00:00:09.934
an area completely off limits to outsiders.

00:00:09.934 --> 00:00:12.104
Most&nbsp;people on board the submarine  

00:00:12.104 --> 00:00:14.728
have no&nbsp;idea why they're here.

00:00:14.728 --> 00:00:16.771
But some do. 

00:00:16.771 --> 00:00:19.560
They're&nbsp;searching for an underwater telephone cable&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:19.560 --> 00:00:22.352
that connects a brand new Soviet nuclear&nbsp;base

00:00:22.352 --> 00:00:25.880
to its headquarters over 1,000 miles away.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:25.880 --> 00:00:27.348
Attached to the submarine 

00:00:27.348 --> 00:00:29.400
is a custom made&nbsp;device 

00:00:29.400 --> 00:00:31.560
designed to wrap around the cable&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:31.560 --> 00:00:34.321
and record every bit of information 

00:00:34.321 --> 00:00:36.081
that passes&nbsp;through it.

00:00:36.081 --> 00:00:37.471
For 10 years

00:00:37.471 --> 00:00:39.437
 this device secretly fed&nbsp;Americans 

00:00:39.437 --> 00:00:41.636
with a gold mine of information&nbsp;

00:00:41.636 --> 00:00:44.600
until one day, it vanished. 

00:00:44.600 --> 00:00:47.934
By 1970, the US and&nbsp;the Soviet Union

00:00:47.934 --> 00:00:49.999
were deep into the Cold War, 

00:00:49.999 --> 00:00:52.500
and the constant threat of nuclear attacks&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:52.500 --> 00:00:54.721
meant that both sides were desperate for 

00:00:54.721 --> 00:00:57.880
any bit&nbsp;of information they could get their hands on.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:57.880 --> 00:00:58.911
The US learned 

00:00:58.911 --> 00:01:00.981
that a brand new nuclear submarine&nbsp;base 

00:01:00.981 --> 00:01:03.457
had just been built in Petropavlovsk 

00:01:03.457 --> 00:01:05.450
in the&nbsp;far east of Russia. 

00:01:05.450 --> 00:01:07.439
It seemed strategically&nbsp;positioned &nbsp;

00:01:07.439 --> 00:01:09.120
for an attack on the US,&nbsp;

00:01:09.120 --> 00:01:11.017
and so Americans made it their goal 

00:01:11.017 --> 00:01:13.017
to start&nbsp;spying on the base. 

00:01:13.017 --> 00:01:15.284
But instead of sending&nbsp;in real spies 

00:01:15.284 --> 00:01:17.611
or relying on satellite imagery,&nbsp;

00:01:17.611 --> 00:01:20.600
they wanted something more substantial.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:20.600 --> 00:01:22.595
Captain James Bradley

00:01:22.595 --> 00:01:24.554
Director of Undersea&nbsp;Warfare

00:01:24.554 --> 00:01:26.400
 was studying a map of the region&nbsp;

00:01:26.400 --> 00:01:28.521
when it suddenly hit him. 

00:01:28.521 --> 00:01:31.814
Since the base was&nbsp;in such a remote location,

00:01:31.814 --> 00:01:34.192
the Soviets needed&nbsp;to have some way 

00:01:34.192 --> 00:01:35.876
of communicating with the&nbsp;headquarters 

00:01:35.876 --> 00:01:37.410
back in Vladivostok. 

00:01:37.410 --> 00:01:39.866
Radio would&nbsp;have been too easy to hack. &nbsp;

00:01:39.866 --> 00:01:41.550
And so he&nbsp;came to the conclusion 

00:01:41.550 --> 00:01:44.913
that they must have run 
an underwater telephone cable&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:44.913 --> 00:01:47.024
through the sea of&nbsp;Okhotsk.  

00:01:47.024 --> 00:01:49.205
If such a cable did exist,

00:01:49.205 --> 00:01:51.367
intercepting it&nbsp;could give the Americans&nbsp;

00:01:51.367 --> 00:01:52.522
all they needed&nbsp;to know&nbsp;

00:01:52.522 --> 00:01:55.000
about the Soviet's nuclear capabilities.&nbsp;

00:01:55.000 --> 00:01:57.857
It was an idea too good to turn down. 

00:01:57.857 --> 00:02:00.960
And so with the help of the CIA and the Navy,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:00.960 --> 00:02:05.429
Operation Ivy Bells was officially underway.

00:02:05.429 --> 00:02:08.002
But&nbsp;finding a cable hundreds of feet &nbsp;

00:02:08.002 --> 00:02:10.257
below a massive&nbsp;expanse of sea 

00:02:10.257 --> 00:02:12.995
seemed like an impossible task.&nbsp;

00:02:12.995 --> 00:02:16.879
Luckily, Captain Bradley once again had a plan.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:16.879 --> 00:02:19.060
He remembered back to his childhood 

00:02:19.060 --> 00:02:20.668
along the&nbsp;Mississippi River 

00:02:20.668 --> 00:02:23.126
where signs would warn fishing&nbsp;boats&nbsp;

00:02:23.126 --> 00:02:25.404
whenever there was an underwater cable.&nbsp;

00:02:25.404 --> 00:02:28.324
If the Soviet cable did exist, 

00:02:28.324 --> 00:02:31.225
he was sure that there would be similar signs&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:31.225 --> 00:02:33.579
along the Russian&nbsp;coast. &nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:33.579 --> 00:02:35.631
After a month-long journey, 

00:02:35.631 --> 00:02:37.200
the USS Halibut

00:02:37.200 --> 00:02:40.072
finally entered the Sea of Okhotsk. 

00:02:40.072 --> 00:02:43.199
The crew began&nbsp;slowly creeping up the coast

00:02:43.199 --> 00:02:46.285
inspecting the&nbsp;shoreline through a periscope. &nbsp;

00:02:46.285 --> 00:02:49.153
It took over a week&nbsp;of constant searching, 

00:02:49.153 --> 00:02:50.503
but amazingly,

00:02:50.503 --> 00:02:52.869
 they finally&nbsp;came across exactly 

00:02:52.869 --> 00:02:55.179
what Captain Bradley had&nbsp;imagined.

00:02:55.179 --> 00:02:57.200
The submarine anchored itself in place&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:57.200 --> 00:02:58.782
and a team of divers 

00:02:58.782 --> 00:03:01.373
made the dangerous 400 ft&nbsp;descent 

00:03:01.373 --> 00:03:03.757
to start installing the wiretap.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:03.757 --> 00:03:05.771
The device worked by induction 

00:03:05.771 --> 00:03:07.217
and so when&nbsp;a conversation 

00:03:07.217 --> 00:03:08.800
was sent through the cable,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:08.800 --> 00:03:11.112
the electric pulses would be picked up 

00:03:11.112 --> 00:03:14.640
and&nbsp;recorded onto a tape recorder inside the device.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:14.640 --> 00:03:18.319
If the Soviets ever tried 
to raise the cable for&nbsp;maintenance,

00:03:18.319 --> 00:03:20.480
 the device was designed to detach&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:20.480 --> 00:03:23.167
and sink to the bottom of the ocean. 

00:03:23.167 --> 00:03:24.724
After a month&nbsp;of recording, 

00:03:24.724 --> 00:03:26.880
the submarine returned to the device&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:26.880 --> 00:03:28.854
and the tapes were sent back to the US 

00:03:28.854 --> 00:03:31.920
to be&nbsp;decoded and translated by Ronald Pelton,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:31.920 --> 00:03:35.426
an NSA analyst who was fluent in Russian. 

00:03:35.426 --> 00:03:38.017
When&nbsp;the team received the first transcripts,

00:03:38.017 --> 00:03:40.099
 they were&nbsp;amazed. 

00:03:40.099 --> 00:03:44.960
The device had picked up thousands 
of conversations between high ranking Soviets,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:44.960 --> 00:03:48.374
openly talking about what 
kind of nuclear weapons&nbsp;they had, 

00:03:48.374 --> 00:03:49.912
their range limitations, 

00:03:49.912 --> 00:03:52.776
and how ready&nbsp;they were to be put into use. &nbsp;

00:03:52.776 --> 00:03:54.122
Thanks to&nbsp;the wiretap

00:03:54.122 --> 00:03:56.800
the Americans also knew exactly when&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:56.800 --> 00:04:00.417
and where Soviet submarines were heading out to&nbsp;sea

00:04:00.417 --> 00:04:04.067
allowing them to quietly follow them at close&nbsp;range.

00:04:04.067 --> 00:04:05.001
Every month

00:04:05.001 --> 00:04:07.514
the USS Halibut would return&nbsp;to the cable

00:04:07.514 --> 00:04:10.838
 to retrieve the tapes and replace&nbsp;the battery. &nbsp;

00:04:10.838 --> 00:04:12.539
Several years went by, 

00:04:12.539 --> 00:04:15.204
and the device&nbsp;just kept feeding the US &nbsp;

00:04:15.204 --> 00:04:16.960
with crucial information

00:04:16.960 --> 00:04:21.434
but it was all about to come to&nbsp;a mysterious end. &nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:21.434 --> 00:04:24.438
To find information about what happened next, 

00:04:24.438 --> 00:04:26.634
I had to do some&nbsp;serious digging. 

00:04:26.634 --> 00:04:28.934
Russian sites said one thing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:28.934 --> 00:04:31.589
and American sites said something else.&nbsp;

