00:05:44.120 --> 00:05:48.116
After an entire decade of secretly spying&nbsp;on the Soviets, 

00:05:48.116 --> 00:05:50.685
the US wiretap at the bottom of&nbsp;the ocean 

00:05:50.685 --> 00:05:53.100
was about to go silent. 

00:05:53.100 --> 00:05:54.509
In 1981

00:05:54.509 --> 00:05:56.232
an&nbsp;American surveillance satellite 

00:05:56.232 --> 00:05:57.613
showed a group of&nbsp;Soviet ships &nbsp;

00:05:57.613 --> 00:06:01.612
hovering around the exact 
spot where&nbsp;the device was located. 

00:06:01.612 --> 00:06:03.571
The US immediately&nbsp;sent a submarine out

00:06:03.571 --> 00:06:05.330
to try and recover the&nbsp;device, &nbsp;

00:06:05.330 --> 00:06:07.071
but it was too late. 

00:06:07.071 --> 00:06:09.226
The device was gone.&nbsp;

00:06:09.226 --> 00:06:11.798
Only a handful of intelligence officers 

00:06:11.798 --> 00:06:14.000
even&nbsp;knew the wiretap existed. 

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:16.102
So how, after 10&nbsp;years 

00:06:16.102 --> 00:06:19.983
did the Soviets suddenly pinpoint its exact&nbsp;location? 

00:06:19.983 --> 00:06:21.277
As it turned out, 

00:06:21.277 --> 00:06:24.123
the Americans had a&nbsp;spy in their midst.

00:06:24.123 --> 00:06:25.646
 It all started a year earlier&nbsp;

00:06:25.646 --> 00:06:27.197
when a strange phone call was made 

00:06:27.197 --> 00:06:29.838
to the&nbsp;Soviet embassy in Washington. 

00:06:29.838 --> 00:06:33.034
The caller claimed&nbsp;to have 
crucial information for the Soviets&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:33.034 --> 00:06:36.697
and wanted to arrange a meeting in exchange&nbsp;for cash. 

00:06:36.697 --> 00:06:37.603
At the embassy, 

00:06:37.603 --> 00:06:41.067
the man met with KGB&nbsp;officer Vitaly Yurchenko

00:06:41.067 --> 00:06:44.440
and started&nbsp;telling him all about Operation Ivy Bells,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:44.440 --> 00:06:47.334
where the wiretap was located, how it worked,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:47.334 --> 00:06:50.720
and&nbsp;what the Americans 
had learned through the cable.

00:06:50.720 --> 00:06:51.850
As it turned out, &nbsp;

00:06:51.850 --> 00:06:55.600
the mysterious man&nbsp;was 
none other than Ronald Pelton,&nbsp;

00:06:55.600 --> 00:06:56.908
the American analyst 

00:06:56.908 --> 00:06:59.625
who translated the&nbsp;wiretaps messages. &nbsp;

00:06:59.625 --> 00:07:01.711
His life had fallen apart.&nbsp;

00:07:01.711 --> 00:07:04.346
He no longer had his job at the NSA. 

00:07:04.346 --> 00:07:05.659
his wife&nbsp;had left him 

00:07:05.659 --> 00:07:10.128
and he was now bankrupt with over&nbsp;$60,000 of debt. &nbsp;

00:07:10.128 --> 00:07:12.762
And so in a desperate attempt&nbsp;to make money, 

00:07:12.762 --> 00:07:15.334
he decided to sell his secrets.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:15.334 --> 00:07:17.060
Pelton had just given away &nbsp;

00:07:17.060 --> 00:07:19.960
one of&nbsp;America's most top secret missions,&nbsp;

00:07:19.960 --> 00:07:22.358
and it was essentially all for nothing&nbsp;

00:07:22.358 --> 00:07:25.960
since the Soviets only paid him $35,000.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:25.960 --> 00:07:28.555
He was still massively in debt, 

00:07:28.555 --> 00:07:32.500
and it was only&nbsp;a matter of time before he got caught.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:32.500 --> 00:07:33.865
Ironically, 

00:07:33.865 --> 00:07:37.601
the FBI had already wiretapped&nbsp;
the Soviet embassy's phone lines 

00:07:37.601 --> 00:07:40.634
and became&nbsp;instantly 
suspicious when they heard the call.

00:07:40.634 --> 00:07:43.138
But&nbsp;Pelton never gave away his name,

00:07:43.138 --> 00:07:45.600
 and so they had&nbsp;no idea it was him. 

00:07:45.600 --> 00:07:47.183
Over the next few years,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:47.183 --> 00:07:50.286
Pelton continued to meet with KGB officers

00:07:50.286 --> 00:07:52.099
 in&nbsp;Washington and Vienna,

00:07:52.099 --> 00:07:54.099
supplying them with&nbsp;everything he knew 

00:07:54.099 --> 00:07:57.130
about America's attempts to spy&nbsp;on the Soviets. 

00:07:57.130 --> 00:08:01.417
But it was all about to come to&nbsp;an end in one final twist. 

00:08:01.417 --> 00:08:03.320
KGB officer Yurchenko,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:03.320 --> 00:08:05.896
who had taken Pelton's initial call, 

00:08:05.896 --> 00:08:08.206
was&nbsp;on an assignment in Rome. 

00:08:08.206 --> 00:08:10.054
While touring around the Vatican,

00:08:10.054 --> 00:08:12.565
he mysteriously slipped away from his&nbsp;colleagues 

00:08:12.565 --> 00:08:15.212
and headed straight for the US embassy.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:15.212 --> 00:08:16.201
When he was there, 

00:08:16.201 --> 00:08:18.404
he announced that he wanted to&nbsp;change sides 

00:08:18.404 --> 00:08:20.880
and start working for the Americans.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:20.880 --> 00:08:24.965
He was doing the exact same thing that&nbsp;Pelton did.

00:08:24.965 --> 00:08:26.407
 Almost immediately,

00:08:26.407 --> 00:08:27.902
 he was flown to&nbsp;the States 

00:08:27.902 --> 00:08:30.000
and put into a safe house in Virginia

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:32.720
where the CIA began questioning him.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:32.720 --> 00:08:37.285
It wasn't clear exactly why Yurchenko 
had suddenly&nbsp;switched sides.

00:08:37.285 --> 00:08:41.934
 But right away, he started to&nbsp;give 
the Americans some interesting information.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:41.934 --> 00:08:44.209
Although he didn't have a name

00:08:44.209 --> 00:08:47.848
he told them that&nbsp;the man 
who revealed the wiretapping&nbsp;secrets

00:08:47.848 --> 00:08:51.000
 was an NSA analyst with red hair.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:52.582
It wasn't much to go on, 

00:08:52.582 --> 00:08:55.867
but the FBI compiled a&nbsp;list of red-haired analysts &nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:55.867 --> 00:08:58.700
and listened back to the recordings of the phone call,

00:08:58.700 --> 00:09:00.513
and sure&nbsp;enough,

00:09:00.513 --> 00:09:03.480
it matched with Ronald Pelton'sprofile.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:03.480 --> 00:09:05.623
They tracked him down and arrested him,

00:09:05.623 --> 00:09:07.106
 and&nbsp;almost immediately, 

00:09:07.106 --> 00:09:10.093
he admitted to spying for the Soviets. &nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:10.093 --> 00:09:12.559
Pelton was given three life&nbsp;sentences &nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:12.559 --> 00:09:16.956
and ended up serving 30 years in prison until 2015, 

00:09:16.956 --> 00:09:20.960
the longest ever&nbsp;sentence 
served for espionage at the time.

